-- 
Oil Volatility Gains as Futures Fall to Lowest Level in a Week

-- B y   M a r g o t   H a b i b y
-- 
2011-07-11T20:26:16Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-07-11/oil-volatility-gains-as-futures-fall-to-lowest-level-in-a-week.html
Oil options volatility rose as
August futures fell to the lowest level in a week amid concern
that the European debt crisis will spread to  Italy .  Implied volatility for at-the-money options expiring in
September, a measure of expected price swings in futures and a
gauge of options prices, was 29.5 percent as of 3 p.m. in  New
York , up from 28.1 percent July 8. August options expire at the
end of this week.  Crude for August delivery dropped $1.05, or 1.1 percent, to
settle at $95.15 a barrel on the  New York Mercantile Exchange .
Prices have risen 25 percent in the past year. September futures
fell $1.08, or 1.1 percent, to $95.62 a barrel.  The most active contracts in electronic trading today were
August $92.50 puts, with 1,581 lots changing hands. They gained
19 cents to 61 cents a barrel. September $91 puts, the next-most
active option, rose 36 cents to $1.98 a barrel with 1,499 lots
trading. One contract covers 1,000 barrels of crude.  The exchange distributes real-time data for electronic
trading and releases information on floor trading, where the
bulk of options trading occurs, the next business day.  September $115 calls were the most active options traded in
the previous session, with 7,111 lots changing hands. They
slipped 7 cents to 11 cents a barrel. The next-most active
options, August $95 puts, rose 47 cents to $1.01 a barrel on
volume of 5,520.  Open interest was highest for December $120 calls with
43,182 contracts. Next were December $125 calls with 39,927 and
December $100 calls with 39,564.  To contact the reporter on this story:
Margot Habiby in  Dallas  at 
 mhabiby@bloomberg.net .  To contact the editor responsible for this story:
Dan Stets at   dstets@bloomberg.net . 